<P>I doubte not brother Epa|phroditus, but y^t God hath heard these your moste humble prayers &amp; lamentable supplications, and will, (when he seeth conuenient<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">
<PB N="375" REF="190">
time,) send you remedy, and geue you a ioyfull and mery hearte, so that you shall leape vpo~ Sathan, and saye: The Lord is my light &amp; my saluation,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Psal. xxvii</NOTE> whom then shall I feare? The Lorde is the strength of my lyfe, of whome then shall I be afrayde? Though an hoaste of men were layde against me, yet shall not my heart be afrayd. And though there rose vp war against me, yet wyll I put my truste in hym.<NOTE PLACE="marg">i. Cor. xv.</NOTE> Again, death is swalowed vp into victory.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ose. xiii.</NOTE> Death where is thy stynge? Hell where is thy vic|tory? The sting of death is synne, and the strengthe of synne is the lawe. But thankes be vnto God, which hath geuen vs the victory. through our Lord Iesus Christ,<NOTE PLACE="marg">A praier.</NOTE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Epa.</SPEAKER>
<P>O whan will the Lord haue mercy on me, and deliuer me from the greuous assaultes of mine en|nemyes, O Lorde, why hast thou
