legible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> Christes bloud should waxe vi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> and become of no price, sayth S<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> Ambrose, if y^e iustification, which
<PB N="435" REF="220">
commeth by grace were due vnto merites going afore.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Psal. ci<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"></NOTE> Dauid sath in a certayne Psalme, prayse&punc; the Lord. O my soule, and all that is within me, praise his holy name. Prayse the Lord, O my soule and forget not his benefites. Whiche forgeueth all thy sinnes, and hea|leth al thine iniquities. Which sa|ueth thy life from destruction, and crowneth the with mercy and lo|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ing kindnes.<NOTE N="*" PLACE="marg"><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> Note.</NOTE> All good men from the beginning haue attributed &amp; geuen the whole glory of their iu|stification and saluation, not to their own merits and good wor|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">es:<NOTE PLACE="marg">i. Cor. xv.</NOTE> but to the free grace and vn|deserued mercy of God,<NOTE PLACE="marg">i, Cor. i</NOTE> that God maye bee all in all, and that he, whiche reioyseth, should reioyse in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">he Lorde. For the contentation and quietnes of your conscience <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">n this behalf, remember y^t Christ <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ame not to cal y^e iusticiaries, but
